tes the value of two approaches to interpreting decisions, those of "case biography" and "legal archaeology." Both draw upon historical sources neglected in conventional legal scholarship. In doing so, they may challenge—or confirm—the validity as precedent today of classic cases from the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aDecedents' estateszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aDisinheritancezUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aDisinheritancezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aInheritance and successionzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aInheritance and successionzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aLegal maximsvCase studies. 0aMurderxLaw and legislationzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aHistory : American History. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Law. 4aPolitics and Law : Law. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Middle Atlantic (DC, DE, MD, NJ, NY, PA).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2024z978311149259940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849636840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438496368423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438496368/original  a978-3-11-149259-9  SUNY Press eBook Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles